{
  "title": "Documenting CLI Tools Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide explains how to create well-documented command-line interfaces (CLI) for your FastAPI applications using the OpenAPI 3.0 specifications and tools available in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI can be used to build CLI tools by utilizing its powerful dependency injection, routing, and OpenAPI support.",
    "OpenAPI 3.0 provides a standardized format for API documentation, making it an ideal choice for documenting CLI tools as well.",
    "To create a CLI tool with FastAPI, you will need to use the `uvicorn` command-line utility and create a main script to call your FastAPI app.",
    "You can define your CLI arguments using the FastAPI `Query` and `Path` parameters annotated with appropriate types such as `str`, `int`, or even custom types for complex arguments.",
    "Documentation for each API endpoint will automatically be included in your CLI tool's help output when the `--openapi-url` flag is provided to `uvicorn`.",
    "To further enhance documentation, you can use tools like `swagger-ui`, `redocly`, or even generate markdown files from your OpenAPI specification."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "bash",
      "code": "uvicorn myapp:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --reload --openapi-url /openapi.json"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI, Query\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\n@app.get('/example')\ndef example(name: str = Query(None, description='The name to greet')):\n    return {'greeting': f'Hello {name}!'}"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "The examples provided in this explainer are compatible with Python 3.12+ and FastAPI version 0.70.0 or later.",
    "Some features, such as the automatic inclusion of documentation in CLI help output, require using `uvicorn` version 0.17.0 or later."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While FastAPI is an excellent choice for building web APIs, it might not be the best fit for complex, feature-rich command-line applications due to its focus on RESTful web services.",
    "When documenting your CLI tools with FastAPI, keep in mind that the output will primarily be text-based and may require additional formatting or organization to make it user-friendly."
  ]
}

code_examples.code:
from fastapi import FastAPI, Query

app = FastAPI()

@app.get('/example')
def example(name: str = Query(None, description='The name to greet')):
    return {'greeting': f'Hello {name}!'}
